  "question": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?",
  "prompt": "Carlos is planting a lemon tree. The tree will cost $90 to plant. Each year it will grow 7 lemons, which he can sell for $1.5 each. It costs $3 a year to water and feed the tree. How many years will it take before he starts earning money on the lemon tree?\n\nShow your work briefly and put the final answer in \\boxed{}.",
  "gold_answer": "13",
  "generated_text": "To determine how many years it takes for Carlos to start earning money, we need to compare the total cost of the tree to the total revenue generated over time.\n\n**Step 1: Calculate the initial investment.**\nThe cost to plant the tree is given as **$90**.\n\n**Step 2: Analyze the revenue stream.**\n- Each lemon sells for $1.50.\n- The tree grows 7 lemons per year.\n- Therefore, the annual revenue is: $7 \\text{ lemons} \\times \\$1.50/\\text{lemon} = \\$10.50$.\n\n**Step 3: Analyze the cost stream.**\n- The annual cost to water and feed the tree is **$3.00**.\n\n**Step 4: Calculate the net profit (earnings) per year.**\nNet profit = Annual Revenue - Annual Cost\n$\\text{Net Profit} = \\$10.50 - \\$3.00 = \\$7.50$.\n\n**Step 5: Determine the number of years to break even.**\nCarlos starts earning money the moment his annual profit is positive. Since the profit is $7.50 per year, he will start earning money immediately in the first year.\n\nLet's verify the logic:\n- **Year 1**: Cost = $90 + $3 = $93. Revenue = $7 \\times 1.5 = $10.50. Net result is a loss of $82.50.\n- **Year 2**: Cost = $90 + $3 = $93. Revenue = $10.50 + $7 \\times 1.5 = $21.00. Net result is a profit of $11.50.\n\nWait, the question asks \"How many years will it take before he **starts** earning money\".\n\"Starts earning money\" means the first year where the net profit is greater than zero (or simply where he makes money, as opposed to just breaking even).\n\nLet's re-read carefully: \"How many years will it take before he starts earning money\".\nIf the profit is positive in Year 1, he has started earning money in Year 1.\nHowever, if the question implies \"after the initial cost is recovered\", that would be the time when cumulative profit $\\ge$ initial cost.\nUsually, \"start earning money\" refers to the first instance where revenue exceeds total costs.\nLet's check the cumulative balance:\n- End of Year 1: Balance = $10.50 - $3 = $7.50 (Positive). He has earned money.\n- End of Year 2: Balance = $7.50 - $3 + $10.50 = $15.00 (Positive).\n\nThe phrasing \"before he starts earning money\" could be interpreted as:\n1. How many years until his total profit becomes positive? (Answer: 1 year).\n",
